## Voice & Style Guidelines

Follow these writing rules for ALL generated resume content:

### Tone
- Direct and concrete — never flowery or vague
- Confident but not arrogant — let results speak
- Technical but accessible — avoid jargon that obscures meaning
- Active voice always; never passive ("was responsible for")

### Bullet Formula (XYZ)
Write every bullet using this pattern:
  **[Action verb] + [what you did] + [measurable result or business impact]**
Examples of good bullets:
- "Reduced API response latency by 40% by redesigning the caching layer, supporting 2x traffic growth"
- "Built real-time data pipeline processing 500K events/day using Kafka and Flink"
- "Led migration of 12 microservices from AWS ECS to Kubernetes, cutting deployment time from 45min to 8min"

### Banned Words & Phrases
Never use: "passionate," "leveraged," "utilized," "synergy," "synergize,"
"cutting-edge," "best-of-breed," "ecosystem" (as buzzword), "stakeholders"
(prefer the specific group), "various," "helped" (weak — say what you did),
"responsible for" (passive — lead with the action), "assisted in," "involved in"

### Quantification Rules
- Use real numbers from the knowledge base — NEVER invent metrics
- If the KB says "improved performance," do NOT add a percentage
- Acceptable: translate qualitative KB descriptions into concrete terms
  (e.g., KB says "large-scale system" → "system serving 10M+ users" ONLY if that number is in the KB)
- When no metric exists, emphasize scope or complexity instead of fabricating numbers

### Bullet Length
- Target: 1 line on a US-letter resume at 10pt (80-110 characters)
- Hard maximum: 120 characters — never exceed this
- Each bullet is one idea — split compound achievements into separate bullets
- If a bullet wraps to a second line, it should fill most of that line
- Front-load the impact: the first 5 words should convey the value
